Anonymous Sun 16 Sep 2018 02:18:47 No.18302411 Report
Quoted By:
>>18301847
>if CRISPR was magic key to everything, we would have magic results
I do not see the problem with that construction, or how it has any relation to an appreciation for how either CRISPR or genetics in general work. I was agreeing that the real work lies in a much deeper understanding of genetics, and simply possessing a good tool to manipulate stuff is insufficient for producing much in the way of dramatic results.
Learn to parse sentences properly, and don't make godawful highschool comparisons to encryption. You condescending fuck.

>>18301975
Certain things play different roles at different times. Changing the kinetics of dopamine, for instance, might help one tiny thing, but break many other things. A change to these that might be useful in altering the function of one part of an organism may produce catastrophic effects elsewhere. "Numbers produced at runtime" in this analogy are any of the parts of the organism produced somewhere down the line from the transcription of the DNA that might be "reused" in this sense. An alteration in one place having cascading effects on the system elsewhere is a common feature of cryptographic systems, hence some encryption-like characteristics do emerge, which is one origin of the popsci genetics=encryption comparison. DNA itself is very much not an encryption; codons are mappable, and they're fault tolerant in that many of the most likely single-base-pair substitutions result in a codon that corresponds to the same amino acid as the original, meaning the mutation produces minimal change in expression - something which is antithetical to a system built for encryption, unless you think hash collisions are a great idea for security. Genetics is not obfuscated by design; it just grew into it, like spaghetti code.
You are looking for an overly specific comparison if you're trying to compare it directly to mutation/gene swapping or something, or to a particular model of seeded random number generators.

Before I go any further, allow me to reiterate what a lot of the folks on here have said. More than any of the specifics of your story, The technical aspects of your writing and storycraft are key. Make sure your grammar and sentence structure are solid. Pay attention to world building, character building, and crafting an interesting story arc. Do the basics right, and folks are much more likely to be charitable about buying into the details.

Depending on what kind of world you're looking to create for your characters / what type of characters you're looking to create, you can skip a whole lot of detail sweating, and cast them as a guerrilla or resistance fighter. You can chalk up any misses on your part to misses on the part of the main character, and you can get a ton of story out of your main having to learn as they go.

Alternately, you can cast them in a near-earth world, and give yourself a little wiggle room when it comes to tactics and equipment details. See the example to the left of a Russian with a mk14 EBR. Very much a US rifle, but who cares, because cute wolfess.
